        "references": [
            [
                "Federated Learning (FL) ",
                "(McMahan et al., ",
                "2017a",
                ")",
                " enables clients to collaboratively train machine learning models without sharing their local data with other parties. Due to its privacy-preserving nature, FL has attracted considerable attention across various domains in real-world applications ",
                "(Hard et al., ",
                "2018",
                "; Chen et al., ",
                "2019",
                "; Ramaswamy et al., ",
                "2019",
                "; Leroy et al., ",
                "2019",
                "; Byrd & Polychroniadou, ",
                "2020",
                "; Chowdhury et al., ",
                "2022",
                ")",
                ".\nHowever, even though FL does not require clients to share their raw data with other parties, its collaborative nature inadvertently introduces privacy and security vulnerabilities ",
                "(Cao & Gong, ",
                "2022",
                "; Bhagoji et al., ",
                "2019",
                "; Lam et al., ",
                "2021",
                "; Jin et al., ",
                "2021",
                "; Tomsett et al., ",
                "2019",
                "; Chen et al., ",
                "2017",
                "; Tolpegin et al., ",
                "2020",
                "; Kariyappa et al., ",
                "2022",
                "; Zhang et al., ",
                "2022c",
                ")",
                ".\nMalicious clients in FL systems can harm training by\nsubmitting corrupted model updates to disrupt the global model from converging ",
                "(Fang et al., ",
                "2020",
                "; Chen et al., ",
                "2017",
                ")",
                ", or planting backdoors to induce the global model to perform poorly on certain data instances ",
                "(Bagdasaryan et al., ",
                "2020b",
                ", ",
                "a",
                "; Wang et al., ",
                "2020",
                ")",
                ".",
                "Existing literature on defensive mechanisms in FL includes ",
                "(Blanchard et al., ",
                "2017",
                "; Yang et al., ",
                "2019",
                "; Fung et al., ",
                "2020",
                "; Pillutla et al., ",
                "2022",
                "; He et al., ",
                "2022",
                "; Cao et al., ",
                "2022",
                "; Karimireddy et al., ",
                "2020",
                "; Sun et al., ",
                "2019",
                "; Fu et al., ",
                "2019",
                "; Ozdayi et al., ",
                "2021",
                "; Sun et al., ",
                "2021",
                ")",
                ", etc.\nHowever, the inherent limitations of these approaches make them unsuitable for real-world FL systems. Some strategies require prior knowledge about the number of malicious clients within the FL system ",
                "(Blanchard et al., ",
                "2017",
                ")",
                ", while in practice an adversary would not announce their malicious intentions before attacking; other strategies mitigate impacts of potential malicious client submissions by methods that inevitably alter the aggregation results, such as re-weighting the local models ",
                "(Fung et al., ",
                "2020",
                ")",
                ", modifying the aggregation function ",
                "(Pillutla et al., ",
                "2022",
                ")",
                ", and removing local models that tend to be poisoned ",
                "(Blanchard et al., ",
                "2017",
                ")",
                ".\nHowever, in real-world FL systems, attacks happen infrequently. While introducing defenses can mitigate the impact of potential malicious clients, the defense gain outweighs the loss as most real-world training cases are benign and these defenses largely compromise the model quality for all benign cases.\nMoreover, existing defensive mechanisms are deployed at the FL server without any verification for the execution. This means clients cannot verify if the defensive mechanism has been executed honestly and correctly but are forced to trust the server’s reliability.\nThus, a successful anomaly detection approach should simultaneously satisfy the following aspects: ",
                "i",
                ") ",
                "detectability",
                ": it should be able to detect the occurrence of attacks and exclusively handle the cases when attacks happen;\n",
                "ii",
                ") ",
                "identifiability",
                ": if an attack is detected, the strategy should further identify the malicious client models and mitigate (or eliminate) their adversarial impacts without harming the benign ones; and ",
                "iii",
                ") ",
                "verifiability",
                ": the defensive mechanism should be integrated with a verification system to ensure its integrity and honest execution.",
                "In this paper, we propose a two-stage defensive mechanism for anomaly detection that filters out malicious client models in each FL training round while addressing challenges faced by real-world FL systems.\nOur approach first detects whether any attacks have occurred in the current FL iteration based on a ",
                "cross-round detection",
                ". In case of occurrence of attacks, it performs a ",
                "cross-client detection",
                "\nthat evaluates the ",
                "degree of evilness",
                " of each local model and filters out the malicious local models based on the intuition of ",
                "Three-Sigma Rule",
                " ",
                "(Pukelsheim, ",
                "1994",
                ")",
                ".\nOur mechanism integrates a robust verification protocol that utilizes Zero-Knowledge Proof (ZKP) ",
                "(Goldwasser et al., ",
                "1989",
                ")",
                " to guarantee the integrity and honest execution of our defensive mechanism at the FL server. We compare our approach with the state-of-the-art approaches, including Krum ",
                "(Blanchard et al., ",
                "2017",
                ")",
                ", RFA ",
                "(Pillutla et al., ",
                "2022",
                ")",
                ", and Foolsgold ",
                "(Fung et al., ",
                "2020",
                ")",
                " in ",
                "Table",
                " ",
                "1",
                ", and overview our mechanism in Figure ",
                "1",
                ".\nOur contributions are summarized as follows:",
                "i",
                ") Detection of occurrence of attacks (§",
                "3.1",
                ").",
                " We develop a cross-round check to\nidentify the presence of attacks to activate the defense only when warranted, which can avoid altering aggregation results in attack-free scenarios.",
                "ii",
                ") Elimination of malicious submissions (§",
                "3.2",
                ").",
                " Upon the occurrence of attacks, our approach further eliminates malicious client models in the current FL training round without harming the benign local models.",
                "iii",
                ") Rigorous verification protocol (§",
                "4",
                ").",
                " To cultivate trust in the FL system among those benign FL clients,\nour approach utilizes Zero-Knowledge Proof to guarantee that the FL server has executed the defensive mechanism correctly.",
                "iv",
                ") Effective in real-world systems.",
                " Our method is free from any unrealistic prior information and can detect and eliminate impact of malicious client models without harming the benign ones, thus is applicable and effective in real-world FL systems where attacks happen rarely."
            ]
        ]
    },
